%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Drivers of transportation demand}
\label{sec:drivers_of_transportation_demand}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

At the macro scale, 
economic activity is a large driver of demand for transport
(for example, see Figure~\ref{fig:CarbonEmissionsGraph}, which shows
decreased CO$_2$ emissions during recessions).
The U.S.\ Bureau of Transportation Statistics (BTS)
calculates a monthly measure of transportation services 
output~\cite{U.S.-Department-of-Transportation-Bureau-of-Transportation-Statistics:2021uk}
called the ``Transportation Services Index'' (TSI),
which is a weighted and indexed measure of
freight traffic and passenger transport 
in the for-hire transportation industries.
Figure~\ref{fig:TSI} shows the variation of the TSI over time.
(See \citet{Young:2014uh} for information about the index
and how it is calculated.)
Two patterns are evident:
(a) the general growth of the economy over time drives ever-growing demand for transportation services and
(b) recessions (2009) and pandemics (2020) are ways to
reduce demand for transportation services.
In fact, the correlation between economic growth and freight transportation growth
is so strong that the BTS claims transport is a good indicator for economic activity
at the macro level~\cite{U.S.-Department-of-Transportation-Bureau-of-Transportation-Statistics:2021tn}.
The tight links between transportation and economic growth
are one reason that economic growth and energy consumption are correlated.

