%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Transportation sustainability challenges}
\label{sec:transportation_challenges}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Sustainability challenges arising from transportation include
particulate matter (PM) and CO$_2$ emissions, 
both from burning liquid fossil fuels.
Concerns about the effects of PM\index{particulate matter}
on human health go back millennia, and with good cause.
PM emissions are ``the main contributor to human health effects 
[by air pollution] by some margin''~\cite{Fowler2020}.
PM ``is also the form in which most of the long-range transport 
of sulfur and nitrogen-containing pollutants occurs''~\cite{Fowler2020}.
Hippocrates (circa 400 BC) writes about the effects of wood smoke.
Later, coal soot was an additional concern. 
Problems in urban centers intensified with the introduction of early (dirty) internal 
combustion engines.
Since the mid-twentieth century, air quality in North America, Europe and Japan
has improved.
However, emissions in South and East Asia rose in the late twentieth and early 
twenty-first centuries. 
Global SO$_2$ emissions peaked about 1990 and global NO$_x$ emissions peaked around
2018. 
Global ammonia emissions, a key contributor to PM, continues to grow, however.


Figure~\ref{fig:transport_GHG_emissions} shows trends of CO$_2$ transportation emissions by mode
over time.
Passenger cars are the greatest single cause of CO$_2$ emissions from transportation.
One interesting feature of Figure~\ref{fig:transport_GHG_emissions}
is that CO$_2$ emissions peaked in 2000, about a decade before the Great Recession (2007--2009).
The CO$_2$ emissions peak was likely caused by a combination of factors:
record-high prices for liquid transportation fuels in the runup to the Great Recession,
which led drivers to prefer higher-efficiency vehicles, 
which led to a decline total CO$_2$ emissions, 
even as delivery of transportation services rose through the 2000s (Figure~\ref{fig:TSI}).


