%..............................
\paragraph{Electric vehicles}
\label{sec:electric_vehicles}
%..............................

Figure~\ref{fig:auto_gwp} shows two types of environmental impact
(global warming potential\index{global warming potential}
and mineral resource depletion\index{mineral resource depletion})
across the full life cycle\index{life cycle!automobiles}
of automobile use,
from base vehicle manufacturing to end of life disposal,
assuming 150,000~km service.
Internal combustion engine (ICE) vehicles\index{vehicle!internal combustion engine}
are considered to consume regular gasoline (gas).
Electric vehicles (EVs)\index{vehicle!electric} are modeled as using electricity 
generated by two different primary fuel mixes:
a high proportion%
\footnote{
  20\% renewables was also the European Union average
  electricity mix\index{electricity!European mix} 
  when the \citet[Fig.~1]{Hawkins_2012} paper was written (c.~2010)~\cite{European-Environment-Agency:2021vb}
  and upon which the environmental impacts for the ``Ren20'' electricity mix are based.
  The U.S.\ average electricity mix today (2020) 
  is also about 20\% renewable~\cite{U.S.-Energy-Information-Agency:2021tp}, 
  while the European mix is closer to 30\% renewable.
  The UK electricity mix is pushing toward 40\% renewable (37.1\%)~\cite{Evans:2020vj}.
}
%
of renewables (20\%)
or pure coal\index{coal}\index{electricity!from coal}.

Figure~\ref{fig:auto_gwp} shows that EVs are clearly worse than ICE vehicles
in terms of mineral resource depletion~(MRD)\index{resources!mineral!depletion of}.
The material demands for engine and battery fabrication are much higher for EVs 
than for ICE vehicles.
However, EVs \emph{can} provide benefits in terms of global warming potential~(GWP)
relative to ICE vehicles
\emph{if} the electricity source includes renewables (as in the ``Ren20'' electricity mix), 
because of lower lifetime fuel/electricity emissions.
In the case of the European electricity mix,
the global warming benefits of EVs are achieved
despite much larger emissions from battery manufacturing.
However, the global-warming benefits of EVs evaporate
when the electricity is generated from coal,
because of higher electricity-related emissions.
\citet[p.~61]{Hawkins_2012} point out that
``[e]nvironmental evaluations relying solely on fuel and powertrain efficiencies\index{efficiency!powertrain}
miss key differences associated with the production of different vehicle types and
could lead to misguided comparisons across technologies.''


